Build succeeds. Here's what changed and why:

**MSTest v3 removed the `Assert.AreEqual(object, object)` overload.** When both arguments are typed as `object`, the compiler can't resolve to the generic `AreEqual<T>(T, T)` overload automatically.

**Fix:** Add an explicit generic type parameter:

```csharp
// Before (v2)                          // After (v3)
Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual);   → Assert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);
Assert.AreNotEqual(a, b);           → Assert.AreNotEqual<object>(a, b);
Assert.AreSame(obj, obj);           → Assert.AreSame<object>(obj, obj);
```

If your variables had concrete types (e.g., `string`, `int`), the compiler would infer `<T>` automatically and no change would be needed. The `<object>` annotation is only necessary when the compile-time type is `object`.
